{{Infobox language |name=Bezhta |nativename=бежкьалас миц / bežƛʼalas mic |pronunciation={{IPA-cau|ˈbeʒt͡ɬʼɑlɑs mit͡s|}} |states=[[Russia]] |region=Southern [[Dagestan]] |speakers=6,800 |date=2006–2010 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Caucasian |fam1=[[Northeast Caucasian languages|Northeast Caucasian]] |fam2=[[Tsezic languages|Tsezic]] |fam3=Bezhta–Hunzib–Khwarshi |iso3=kap |glotto=bezh1248 |glottorefname=Bezhta |notice=IPA }} The '''Bezhta''' (or '''Bezheta''') language (Bezhta: '''бежкьалас миц''', ''bežƛʼalas mic'', {{IPA-cau|ˈbeʒt͡ɬʼɑlɑs mit͡s|pron}}), also known as '''Kapucha''' (from the name of [[Kapucha (village)|a large village]]<ref>Shirin Akiner, ''Islamic Peoples of the Soviet Union'', 2nd ed. (KPI, Distributed by Routledge & Kegan Paul, 1986: {{ISBN|0-7103-0188-X}}), p. 253.</ref>), belongs to the [[Tsezic languages|Tsezic]] group of the [[North Caucasian languages|North Caucasian language family]]. It is spoken by about 6,200 people in southern [[Dagestan]], [[Russia]]<ref name="Ethnologue">[http://www.ethnologue.com/show_language.asp?code=kap Ethnologue entry for Bezhta]</ref>
Bezhta can be divided into three dialects – [[Bezhta Proper dialect|Bezhta Proper]], [[Tlyadal]] and [[Khocharkhotin]]<ref name="Ethnologue" /> – which are spoken in various villages in the region. Its closest linguistic relatives are [[Hunzib language|Hunzib]] and [[Khwarshi language|Khwarshi]].<ref name="Schulze09"/> Bezhta is unwritten, but various attempts have been made to develop an official orthography for the language. The [[Bezhta people]] use [[Avar language|Avar]] as the literary language. The first book ever printed in Bezhta was the [[Gospel of Luke]].<ref name=IBT200012/>
==Phonology== {{expand section|date=January 2010}} Bezhta has a rich consonantal and – unlike its relatives [[Tsez language|Tsez]] and [[Avar language|Avar]] – a relatively large vowel inventory (18 distinct vowel phonemes),{{citation needed|date=January 2010}} compared to other languages of the same family.
Consonants: {| class="wikitable" !rowspan=2 colspan=2|&nbsp; !rowspan=2|[[Bilabial consonant|Bilabial]] !colspan=2|[[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar]] !colspan=2|[[Velar consonant|Velar]] !rowspan=2|[[Postalveolar consonant|Alveolopalatal]] !rowspan=2|[[Uvular consonant|Uvular]] !rowspan=2|[[Pharyngeal consonant|Pharyngeal]] !rowspan=2|[[Glottal consonant|Glottal]] |- align="center" !<small>central</small> !<small>[[lateral consonant|lateral]]</small> !<small>[[lateral consonant|lateral]]</small> !<small>central</small> |- align="center" !colspan=2|[[Nasal consonant|Nasal]] |{{IPA|m}} |{{IPA|n}} |&nbsp; |&nbsp; |&nbsp; |&nbsp; |&nbsp; |&nbsp; |&nbsp; |- align="center" !rowspan=3|[[Plosive consonant|Plosive]] !<small>[[voicelessness|voiceless]]</small> |{{IPA|p}} |{{IPA|t}} | | |{{IPA|k}} | |{{IPA|q}} | |{{IPA|ʔ}} |- align="center" !<small>[[voice (phonetics)|voiced]]</small> | {{IPA|b}} | {{IPA|d}} | | |{{IPA|ɡ}} | | | | |- align="center" !<small>[[ejective consonant|ejective]]</small> |{{IPA|pʼ}} |{{IPA|tʼ}} | | |{{IPA|kʼ}} | |{{IPA|qʼ}} | | |- align="center" !rowspan=2|[[Affricate consonant|Affricate]] !<small>voiceless</small> | |{{IPA|t͡s}} |colspan=2|{{IPA|t͡ɬ ~ k͡ʟ̝̊}} | |{{IPA|t͡ʃ}} | | | |- align="center" !<small>ejective</small> | |{{IPA|t͡sʼ}} |colspan=2|{{IPA|t͡ɬʼ ~ k͡ʟ̝̊ʼ}} | |{{IPA|t͡ʃʼ}} | | | |- align="center" !rowspan=2|[[Fricative consonant|Fricative]] !<small>voiceless</small> | |{{IPA|s}} |{{IPA|ɬ}} | |{{IPA|x}} |{{IPA|ʃ}} |{{IPA|χ}} |{{IPA|ħ}} |{{IPA|h}} |- align="center" !<small>voiced</small> | |{{IPA|z}} | | | |{{IPA|ʒ}} |{{IPA|ʁ}} |{{IPA|ʕ}} | |- align="center" !colspan=2|[[Trill consonant|Trill]] | |{{IPA|r}} | | | | | | | |- align="center" !colspan=2|[[Approximant consonant|Approximant]] | | |{{IPA|l}} | |{{IPA|w}} |{{IPA|j}} | | | |}
==Morphology== {{expand section|date=January 2010}} Bezhta is mostly [[agglutination|agglutinative]] and the vast amount of [[locative case]]s makes its case system particularly rich. The verb morphology is relatively simple, though. It is an [[ergative language]].{{citation needed|date=January 2010}}
==Numerals== Unlike [[Tsez language|Tsez]], Bezhta has a decimal system with the word for twenty being an exception.{{citation needed|date=January 2010}}
{| !&nbsp; !Latin !Cyrillic |- |1 |hõs |гьо<sup>н</sup>с |- |2 |qʼona |къона |- |3 |łana |лъана |- |4 |ṏqʼönä |оь<sup>н</sup>къоьнаь |- |5 |łina |лъина |- |6 |iłna |илъна |- |7 |aƛna |алIна |- |8 |beƛna |белIна |- |9 |äčʼena |аьчIена |- |10 |acʼona |ацIона |- |20 |qona |хъона |- |100 |hõsčʼitʼ / -čʼitʼ |гьо<sup>н</sup>счIитI / -чIитI |- |1000 |hazay |гьазай |}
* Multiples of 10 higher than 20 are formed by adding the suffix '''-yig''' ('''-йиг''') to the multiplier. Hence, the word for 30 is '''łanayig''' ('''лъанайиг'''). * Compound numbers are formed by [[wiktionary:juxtaposition|juxtaposition]], the smaller numbers following the greater ones. The number 47 is thus expressed as '''ṏqʼönäyig aƛna''' ('''оь<sup>н</sup>къоьнаьйиг алIна''').
==Sample of the Bezhta language== This is a passage taken from the [[Gospel of Luke]]<ref name="Gospel" /> written in a Cyrillic orthography based on [[Avar language|Avar]] and [[Chechen language|Chechen]], a Latinized transcription and one in [[International Phonetic Alphabet|IPA]]. {| !CYRILLIC !LATIN TRANSCRIPTION !IPA TRANSCRIPTION !TRANSLATION |- |Гьогцо гьоллохъа нисос: |Hogco holloqa nisos: |{{IPA|[hoɡ.t͡so holː.o.qɑ ni.sos}} |Jesus said to the followers: |- |Доьъа богьцалаъ вагьда̄ ниса: |Dö'a bohcala' wahdā nisa: |{{IPA|dɜʔ.ɑ boh.t͡sɑ.lɑʔ wɑh.dɑː ni.sɑ}} |When you pray, pray like this: |- |«Йа̄ Або, Дибо ца̄<sup>н</sup> аьдамла̄ илагьияб бикӀзи йовала, |«Yā Abo, Dibo cā̃ ädamlā ilahiyab bikʼzi yowala, |{{IPA|jɑː ʔɑ.bo, di.bo t͡sɑ̃ː ʔa.dɑm.lɑː ʔi.lɑ.hi.jɑb bikʼzi jo.wɑ.lɑ}} |"O Father, we pray that your name will always be kept holy, |- |Дибо Парчагьлъи йо<sup>н</sup>къала; |Dibo Parčahłi yõqʼala; |{{IPA|di.bo pɑr.t͡ʃɑh.ɬi jõ.qʼɑ.lɑ}} |we pray that your kingdom will come; |- |Шибаб водиъ баццас баьба илол нилӀа; |Šibab wodi' baccas bäba ilol niƛa; |{{IPA|ʃi.bɑb wo.diʔ bɑt͡sː.ɑs ba.bɑ ʔi.lol ni.tɬɑ}} |give us the food we need for each day; |- |Илла мунагьла̄кьас кьодос тилӀки, судлӀо нисода илена къацӀцӀола илол кешлъи йо̄вакьас кьодос тилӀбакца. |Illa munahlāƛʼas ƛʼodos tiƛki, sudƛo nisoda ilena qʼacʼcʼola ilol kešłi yōwaƛʼas ƛʼodos tiƛbakca. |{{IPA|ʔi.lːɑ mu.nɑh.lɑːtɬʼ.ɑs tɬʼo.dos ti.tɬki, sud.tɬo ni.sɔ.dɑ ʔi.le.nɑ qʼɑt͡sʼː.o.lɑ ʔi.lol keʃ.ɬi joː.wɑ.tɬʼɑs tɬʼo.dos ti.tɬbɑk.t͡sɑ}} |forgive us the sins we have done, because we forgive every person that has done wrong to us. |- |Ми илос гьаьл бикъелална уь<sup>н</sup>холъа̄къа.» |Mi ilos häl biqʼelalna ü̃xołāqʼa.» |{{IPA|mi ʔi.los hal bi.qʼe.lɑl.nɑ ʔɨ̃.χo.ɬɑː.qʼɑ]}} |And don't let us be tempted." |}
