[[File:Human_Rights_Watch_says_nearly_6000_people_have_been_disabled_since_the_Saudi-led_coalition_began_airstrikes_nine_months_ago.jpg|alt=In January 2016, Human Rights Watch said nearly 6000 people had been disabled since the Saudi-led coalition began airstrikes in 2015.|thumb|In January 2016, [[Human Rights Watch]] said nearly 6000 people had been disabled since the Saudi-led coalition began airstrikes in 2015.|300x300px]]
'''Disability in Yemen''' has been increasing over time, especially because of increased conflict in the area. [[Disability|Disabled people]] in [[Yemen]] face many challenges due to [[poverty]], lack of accessible infrastructure, [[Sex segregation|gender segregation]] and more. The government of Yemen has passed laws to help protect the rights of the disabled in their country, but not all laws are equally enforced.

== Demographics ==
A 2004 estimate indicated that there were around 380,000 disabled people in Yemen.<ref name=":3">{{Cite news|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/world/middle-east/yemens-disabled-face-segregation#full|title=Yemen's disabled face segregation|last=Al Qadhi|first=Mohammed|date=8 November 2008|work=The National|access-date=2017-06-01|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en-US}}</ref> A paper produced by the [[United Nations]] (UN) in 2009 estimated the number at between 3 and 5% of the population.{{Sfn|ESCWA|2009|p=4}} The Yemen government recorded around 150,000 Yemeni people with disabilities,<ref name=":5">{{Cite news|url=http://www.yementimes.com/en/1698/health/2699/Resources-few-for-autistic-children-Yemeni-law-fails-to-guarantee-rights-of-persons-with-disabilities.htm|title=Resources few for autistic children Yemeni law fails to guarantee rights of persons with disabilities|last=Hassan|first=Najila'a|date=29 July 2013|work=Yemen Times|access-date=2017-06-01|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en}}</ref> while in 2014, the [[Yemeni Handicapped Forum]] revealed that there were more than two million people living with some type of disability in Yemen.<ref name=":2">{{Cite news|url=http://www.yementimes.com/en/1839/news/4648/Local-NGO-Number-of-disabled-citizens-in-Yemen-exceeds-two-million.htm|title=Local NGO: Number of disabled citizens in Yemen exceeds two million|last=Al-Moshki|first=Ali Ibrahim|date=4 December 2014|work=Yemen Times|access-date=2017-06-01|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en}}</ref> The ongoing conflict in Yemen has added to the number of people who are disabled.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/tr/contents/articles/originals/2016/11/yemen-war-recovery-social-economy-problems.html|title=Is Yemen falling into an abyss?|last=Nasser|first=Amal|date=2016-11-28|work=Al-Monitor|access-date=2017-06-01|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=}}</ref> There have been around 28,500 people injured in Yemen since March of 2015.<ref name=":4">{{Cite news|url=http://www.handicap-international.us/yemen_helping_war_survivors_recover_physically_and_mentally|title=Yemen: Helping War Survivors Recover Physically and Mentally|work=Handicap International|access-date=2017-06-01}}</ref>

The number of people in Yemen diagnosed with [[autism]] has increased over time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.yementimes.com/en/1581/report/995/Summer-camp-aims-to-support-autistic-children.htm|title=Summer camp aims to support autistic children|last=Al-Muraqab|first=Ashraf|date=14 June 2012|work=Yemen Times|access-date=2017-06-03|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en}}</ref> 

Disabled individuals make up less than 1% of the workforce in the country.{{Sfn|ESCWA|2009|p=7}} More individuals with disability live in [[Rural area|rural areas]] of Yemen.{{Sfn|MoSAL|2010|p=13}} In addition, those in the lowest [[Income bracket|income brackets]] are twice as likely to be disabled as people in the highest brackets as reported in 2005.{{Sfn|MoSAL|2010|p=13}}

== Causes ==
In many cases disability in Yemen could be prevented.{{Sfn|ESCWA|2009|p=4}} People in Yemen have disabilities related to [[Spinal cord injury|spinal cord injuries]] which could be corrected with surgery.<ref name=":3" /> Incidents of [[Poliomyelitis|polio]] still occur in Yemen,{{Sfn|Grut|Ingstad|2006|p=18}} with 485 cases occurring in 2005 and 2006.{{Sfn|Ingstad|Baider|Grut|2011|p=147}} Approximately 30% of disabilities in Yemen may result from [[Congenital disorder|congenital]] conditions or from complications during [[Birth|delivery]] as reported in 2003.{{Sfn|MoSAL|2010|p=14}}

A study released by [[Ibrahim Omran]] ties most cases of disability to war and conflict in Yemen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nationalyemen.com/2012/06/16/perseverance-and-pain-for-yemens-disabled/|title=Perseverance and pain for Yemen’s disabled|last=Al-Arashi|first=Fakhri|date=2012|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-06-01}}</ref> Because of armed conflict in the region, thousands of Yemeni people have lost limbs since 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.icrc.org/en/document/scars-war-yemens-disabled|title=The scars of war: Yemen's disabled|date=2016-05-23|work=International Committee of the Red Cross|access-date=2017-05-31|language=en}}</ref> Traffic accidents, conflicts between tribes, [[Land mine|land mines]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.icrc.org/en/document/yemen-disability-not-obstacle|title=Yemen: Disability is not an obstacle|date=2016-12-02|work=International Committee of the Red Cross|access-date=2017-06-01|language=en}}</ref> spinal fever, [[Genetic disorder|genetic diseases]] and [[malnutrition]] are also leading causes of disability in Yemen.<ref name=":3" /> Marriages between close [[Cousin|cousins]] also increases changes of genetic causes of disability.{{Sfn|Grut|Ingstad|2006|p=27}}

== Cultural attitudes towards disability ==
The major religion of Yemen, [[Islam]], emphasizes caring for the disabled and enduring hardship. This attitude affects the way that many Yemeni people face the challenges of disability.{{Sfn|Ingstad|Baider|Grut|2011|p=144}}

Families of disabled people and those who are disabled can, however, face [[social stigma]].{{Sfn|ESCWA|2009|p=5}} Some people in Yemen believe that mothers can pass a disability to their children.{{Sfn|ESCWA|2009|p=5}} Families have kept disabled people under virtual [[house arrest]] in some situations because of the shame associated with disability.<ref name=":3" /> Disabled women have difficulty seeing themselves getting married, although disabled men in Yemen imagined they would be able to marry almost anyone.{{Sfn|Grut|Ingstad|2006|p=24}}

Individuals with disability in Yemen can be denied access to education, employment, access to healthcare and have difficulties with public spaces and transportation that are not designed to accommodate disabled people.{{Sfn|ESCWA|2009|p=5}}<ref name=":3" />

===Sport===
Yemen has participated in the Paralympic Games only once, the [[Yemen at the 1992 Summer Paralympics|1992 Summer Games in Barcelona]].<ref>{{IPC medals | npc = YEM }}</ref> {{As of|June 2017}} the Yemen Paralympic Committee is suspended from the [[International Paralympic Committee]].<ref>https://www.paralympic.org/yemen-suspended</ref>

== Policy ==
The government organization responsible for helping disabled individuals is the [[Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour (Yemen)|Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour]] (MoSAL).{{Sfn|ESCWA|2009|p=9}} MoSAL also has a Disability Fund (DF).{{Sfn|Grut|Ingstad|2006|p=16}} Yemen is one of the countries who has ratified the UN [[Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities]].<ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2015/12/03/people-disabilities-added-risk-war-displacement|title=People with Disabilities at Added Risk in War, Displacement|date=2015-12-03|work=Human Rights Watch|access-date=2017-06-01|language=en}}</ref> The [[Social Fund for Development (Yemen)|Social Fund for Development]] (SFD) is a social safety net created in 1997 which targets at-risk people in Yemen, including people with disabilities.{{Sfn|Grut|Ingstad|2006|p=16}} In 2008, the SFD supported programs for 1,083 children with disabilities.{{Sfn|MoSAL|2010|p=16}} The government of Yemen, in 2007, created a National Disability Strategy which "outlines the vision, objectives and principles of a 'rights-based' approach to disability for Yemen."{{Sfn|MoSAL|2010|p=8}}

The [[Ministry of Education (Yemen)|Ministry of Education]] in Yemen has not always had enough funding to support disabled students.<ref name=":2" /> There are only a few schools for disabled children and these are only in Yemen's cities.{{Sfn|Grut|Ingstad|2006|p=21}} Most people with disabilities in Yemen lack education and only 23.6% of those with disabilities have finished [[secondary school]], according to a 2005 study.{{Sfn|MoSAL|2010|p=16}}

=== Non-governmental organizations ===
Various [[Non-governmental organization|non-governmental organizations]] (NGOs) operate in Yemen to help people with disabilities, however, many are underfunded.<ref name=":2" /> Organizations like [[Handicap International]] have helped by donating [[Mobility aid|mobility aids]] and offer [[Psychology|psychological]] support for people in Yemen.<ref name=":4" /> The [[Yemen Center for Autism]] (YCA) in [[Sana'a]] helps individuals with [[autism]] and their families.<ref name=":5" /> However, YCA has had trouble meeting the needs of their clients.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.yementimes.com/en/1625/report/1609/Yemen-Center-for-Autism-struggling-%E2%80%98alone%E2%80%99-to-serve-a-growing-population-nationwide.htm|title=Yemen Center for Autism: struggling ‘alone’ to serve a growing population nationwide|last=Al-Wesabi|first=Sadeq|date=14 November 2012|work=Yemen Times|access-date=2017-06-03|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en}}</ref> The Altahadi Foundation, also in Sana'a, helps disabled women and girls.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.islamic-relief.org/wheelchairs-and-walkers-distributed/|title=Wheelchairs and Walkers Distributed|last=|first=|date=|website=Islamic Relief|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-06-01}}</ref>

=== Legislation ===
The Law for the Welfare of Disabled (Law Number 2, 2002) is considered by the [[United Nations|UN]] to be the principal document pertaining to people with disability.{{Sfn|ESCWA|2009|p=7}} Other laws covering disability include articles 115 - 123 of the Child Law (Number 45, 2002) and Public Law Number 61, 1999.{{Sfn|ESCWA|2009|p=7}} Public Law (61/1999) guarantees that disabled people have the same rights as non-disabled people under the [[Constitution of Yemen]].{{Sfn|Grut|Ingstad|2006|p=15}} It also "allocates the responsibility for disability to the Disability Fund.{{Sfn|MoSAL|2010|p=16}} Civil Service Law Number 19 in 1991 and Labor Law Number 5 in 1995 both address quotas to be met for the employment of people with disabilities.{{Sfn|MoSAL|2010|p=16}} Building Code 19 of 2002 is intended to create [[Accessibility|accessible]] [[infrastructure]].{{Sfn|MoSAL|2010|p=16}}

Disabled people, however, have claimed that while the laws Yemen has created are good, they are rarely [[Coming into force|enforced]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.yementimes.com/en/1780/variety/3842/People-with-disabilities--freedom-of-expression.htm|title=People with disabilities & freedom of expression|last=|first=|date=13 May 2014|work=Yemen Times|access-date=2017-06-01|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en}}</ref> Wording of the laws is also often vague, making it difficult to enforce these laws on behalf of disabled people.<ref name=":5" />

== Unique challenges ==
Because of ongoing conflict in Yemen, people with disabilities face problems such as lack of services and inability to access buildings. [[Rubble]] in the streets can make it difficult for those with physical disabilities to access services.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2015/05/11/dispatches-disabilities-yemen-left-rubble|title=Dispatches: With Disabilities in Yemen, Left in the Rubble|date=2015-05-11|work=Human Rights Watch|access-date=2017-06-01|language=en}}</ref> Areas that have received heavy bombing have had to discontinue services to people with disabilities.<ref name=":0" /> In late 2015, [[Saudi Arabia|Saudi]]-led coalitions bombed the Al Noor Center for Care and Rehabilitation of the Blind in Sana'a.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.vice.com/article/saudi-arabia-bombed-a-rehabilitation-center-for-blind-people-in-yemen|title=The Saudi Coalition Bombed A Rehabilitation Center for Blind People in Yemen|last=Oakford|first=Samuel|date=5 January 2016|work=VICE News|access-date=2017-06-03|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en-US}}</ref>

[[Human Rights Watch]] (HRW) states that people with disabilities are at increased risk during times of crisis and conflict.<ref name=":1" /> People with disabilities and their families have had difficulty leaving conflict zones.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=50769|title=Yemen conflict death toll nears 650, with UN rights office spotlighting plight of 3 million disabled|last=|first=|date=2015-05-05|website=UN News Service Section|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-06-01}}</ref> On December 3, 2016, disabled Yemenis rallied on the [[United Nations' International Day of Persons with Disabilities|International Day of Persons with Disabilities]], asking that the conflict in Yemen end.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/photo/2016-12/04/c_135878684.htm|title=Disabled people rally to call for early end to crisis in Yemen|last=|first=|date=4 December 2016|website=Xinhua|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-06-01}}</ref>

Because most Yemeni people live in rural areas outside of cities, it is difficult to access services for people with disability.{{Sfn|Grut|Ingstad|2006|p=27}} Due to the poverty of many disabled Yemeni people, [[Assistive technology|assistive devices]] are too expensive to purchase.{{Sfn|Grut|Ingstad|2006|p=35}} Government services meant to help disabled people in poverty must be requested in person in Sana'a and require that the applicant be [[Literacy|literate]].{{Sfn|Ingstad|Baider|Grut|2011|p=148}}

=== Gender and disability ===
Disabled women in Yemen face unique challenges because of the conservative attitude towards women in the country.<ref name=":3" /> Disabled women in 2004 had [[Literacy|illiteracy]] rates as high as 87 to 90 percent.<ref name=":3" />  In some cases, however, education for disabled girls was actively encouraged as an alternative opportunity.{{Sfn|Ingstad|Baider|Grut|2011|p=147}}

Women in Yemen who become disabled as adults and are unable to perform their usual roles can lose their sense of self-worth.{{Sfn|Ingstad|Baider|Grut|2011|p=142}}

Non-disabled women are often prevented from getting an education or marrying out of the family unit if there are disabled members of her family; she is expected to help care for the family members with disabilities.{{Sfn|Ingstad|Baider|Grut|2011|p=143}}

Female teachers have rejected teaching disabled men because of the stratification of Yemeni society where men and women do not normally interact with one another.{{Sfn|Ingstad|Baider|Grut|2011|p=147}}

